    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-12-03T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-12-03T19:00:00-05:00" n="585"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d585">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/10519: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-12-03T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 3, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1182. Your no. 1390 of November 26, 10 a.m. Metals Reserve states that its option
                    provides that tin need not be accepted above an amount equal to 50% of tungsten
                    shipments. However, this does not mean that the tin would be shipped if there
                    were enough tungsten available to take all plane space. The limitation is to
                    apply only at our option in case there is insufficient tungsten to fill plane
                    space.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
